We obtain energy from food that is expended through 4 unique pathways (together termed total daily energy expenditure or TDEE). There are nuances within these 4 pathways that determine the extent of the total energy that is expended. Let's dive into an explanation.
RMR is the largest component of energy expenditure, accounting for around 60% to 65% of TDEE. This percentage is quite stable over our lifetime but there are certain variables that impact it. RMR is closely related to our body composition, with higher levels of fat-free mass meaning a higher RMR. Additionally, gender and age-related differences are seen. Finally, chronic energy restriction and/or excessive exercise regimes can downregulate RMR levels.
Typically, non-exercise activity thermogenesis, or NEAT, accounts for 10 to 15% of TDEE but this can be lower or higher depending on the individual. Body composition impacts NEAT, while lifestyle and behavioral tendencies are the greatest impacting factors. Those with more sedentary lifestyles and behaviors will have drastically lower NEAT levels. Step counting is a good barometer of NEAT levels.
Exercise Activity Thermogenesis is all of the purposeful exercises you do in a day, and is usually characterized by moderately high intensity, heavy breathing, and sweating. Thus, the intensity, duration, and mode of exercise have major impacts on the extent of the energy that you'll expend.
The energy cost of eating is around 10% of TDEE but is impacted by diet composition. Protein has a much higher energy cost (to break down) than both carbohydrates and fat. As a side note, apart from alcohol, protein is the nutrient that is least likely for the body to store as fat. This would suggest a diet high in protein would have added benefits for someone wanting to lose weight and/or body fat.

It is easy to get "stuck," feeling unable to get moving because of sitting all day or thinking that if you don't get a 30-90 minutes gym session in, then what is the point? 
My advice: Take micro exercises/breaks which are regular, small, biologically meaningful breaks from being stuck in one position, typically those at work. 
These can be termed “movement snacks,” of simple and brief strengthening exercises designed to strengthen the primary muscle groups.
People who would benefit the most from micro-exercise are
•	Office workers 
•	Students
•	People with elevated levels of personal commitment (kids/work) and blocked little free time
•	People who tend to "sit" for extended periods of time
An activity/step tracker can be a meaningful way to track the difference between these micro-breaks to have a way to track your energy expenditure. 
The main point is, to get moving....even if for short periods of time. I hope this helps!

Here is a follow-up post to my original protein post. I decided to start at the very beginning, laying the groundwork for the new direction of my page!
Let's start with protein, shall we?
Protein Requirements:
What are proteins and what do they do? Proteins are large, complex molecules that play many critical roles in the body. They do most of the work in cells and are required for the structure, function, and regulation of the body’s tissues and organs.
Proteins are made up of hundreds or thousands of smaller units called amino acids, which are attached to one another in long chains. There are 20 different types of amino acids that can be combined to make a protein. The sequence of amino acids determines each protein’s unique 3-dimensional structure and its specific function. Amino acids are coded by combinations of three DNA building blocks (nucleotides), determined by the sequence of genes.
Individuals trying to maximize the skeletal muscle adaptations to training with protein ingestion should focus on determining and implementing the following:
1.	Daily protein requirements: 1.6 – 2.4 g/kg or .24g/kg/meal (these estimates are for young healthy people, the elderly would require more, ~.40g/kg/meal)
2.	Feeding pattern: identify a feeding strategy that fits consistently within your lifestyle. You do not have to adhere to this always, as long as you achieve your daily protein requirements.
3.	Protein quality: Focus on individual or combinations of protein sources that meet critical thresholds of leucine (~2.5g) with a supporting cast of essential amino acids. Identify supplement & whole food options that are consistent with your preferences, health circumstances, and ethically driven dietary decisions.
Notably, vegetarians can still achieve all of the above by using a combination of high-quality protein plant sources. Whatever your dietary or lifestyle circumstances, intelligently select your approach to optimize consistency, adherence, and enjoyment of the process designed to achieve it. The capacity individuals have to personalize their approach in an effort to maintain flexibility in programming characteristics that drive sustainability.

Carbohydrates are an essential part of a healthy diet, and they provide many important nutrients. Being mindful of the micronutrients they contain can help with making healthful dietary choices.
Food for thought:
•	Focus on eating fiber-rich fruits and vegetables. Aim for whole fresh, frozen, and canned fruits and vegetables without added sugar. Or have measured portions of fruit juices and dried fruits, which are concentrated sources of natural sugar, but do have more calories. Whole fruits and vegetables have many health benefits. They add fiber, water, and bulk, which help you feel fuller on fewer calories.
•	Choose whole grains. Whole grains are better sources than refined grains for fiber and other important nutrients, such as B vitamins. Refined grains go through a process that strips out parts of the grain — along with some of the nutrients and fiber.
•	Stick to low-fat dairy products. Milk, cheese, yogurt, and other dairy products are good sources of calcium, protein, vitamin D, potassium, and other vitamins and minerals. Consider the low-fat versions, and watch out for dairy products that have added sugar.
•	Eat more beans, peas, and lentils. Beans, peas, and lentils are among the most versatile and nutritious foods. They are typically low in fat and high in folate, potassium, iron, and magnesium, and they have useful fats and fiber. They are a good source of protein and can be a healthy substitute for meat, which has more saturated fat and cholesterol.
•	Limit added sugars. Added sugar probably isn't harmful in small amounts, but there's no health benefit with added sugar. The main issue is that eating or drinking too many foods with sugar increases the daily caloric intake, making body composition goals more challenging.
The next part of this equation is choosing the appropriate quantities of carbohydrates. Get that part right and you can still eat carbs and reach your physique goals! After protein and total caloric needs are determined, there is room to move between your fat and carbohydrates and is based on personal preference.

Dietary Fats – The Basics.
Dietary fats are essential to give your body energy and support cell function. They also help protect your organs and help keep your body warm. Fats help your body absorb nutrients and produce important hormones.
There are four major dietary fats in food:
1.	Saturated fats
2.	Trans fats
3.	Monounsaturated fats
4.	Polyunsaturated fats
There are nine calories in every gram of fat, regardless of what type of fat it is. Fats are more energy-dense than carbohydrates and proteins, which provide four calories per gram.
Consuming more calories than are utilized – regardless of the source – can lead to weight gain. Consuming elevated levels of saturated or trans fats can also lead to heart disease and stroke. Health experts recommend replacing saturated fats and trans fats with monounsaturated fats and polyunsaturated fats – while still maintaining a nutritionally-adequate diet.
Eating foods with fat is definitely part of a healthy diet. To choose healthier fats, use liquid non-tropical plant oils; low-fat or nonfat instead of full-fat dairy; and, if you eat meat, choose lean meat, or poultry. Remember to balance the number of calories you eat from all foods with the number of calories you use through Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE).
A healthy diet can include the foods you love! Balance your portions (hit close to your macros totals) and choices to emphasize a healthy overall way of eating. An important consideration is balanced decision-making, especially with fats.

Food provides us with nutrients that play one or more physiological or biochemical roles in the body. There are 6 nutrient categories, three being the macronutrients of carbohydrates, fat, and protein with the remaining 3 consisting of water, vitamins, and minerals. 
The functions of each can be further categorized into 3 different areas as shown in the infographic. Once we get past the basics, then what? How do you determine how much of any of it you should be eating? Why is everyone counting macros? Simply stated, it works. If you are training properly and you hit appropriate macro targets, you will make progress in creating an aesthetically pleasing physique. You are not doomed to eternally eating tilapia and asparagus in order to be stage ready. If you are looking for a sustainable way to reach your physique goals, it is undeniable that flexible dieting works. 
Nonetheless, food selection can still be a tremendously valuable tool in your arsenal, whether you’re aiming to gain muscle or lose fat. Different foods can have different effects on satiety, and you may also find certain foods that habitually trigger you to overeat. Just because a wide variety of foods can fit into your macros, doesn’t mean that food selection is irrelevant. These choices do matter from a nutritional perspective as well as how satiated your feel after eating.
While flexible dieting unequivocally works making optimal food choices involves considering more than just caloric content and macronutrient composition. It’s important to appreciate that mood, emotion, and food occupy go hand in hand, and food choices can prompt us to eat more and influence our emotions. 
Whether bulking or cutting, you can use this information to your advantage. When bulking, there may be benefits to opting for low-satiety and palatable food choices to increase your caloric intake for the day. When cutting, it may be beneficial to avoid hyper-palatable trigger foods, select foods with high satiety ratings, and even implement some anti-triggering foods as needed.

Calories. 

The human body consists of many types of energy-consuming cells within a variety of organs that work in systems to ensure we remain alive and are able to function.
These cells require energy to function so we need to obtain energy from food to remain alive. Even though our body has natural reserves of energy (i.e., fat stores, muscle glycogen, and liver glycogen) most of our energy comes from our nutrition. The food we eat contains energy in the form of calories in the macronutrients, of which there are three (protein carbohydrates, and fats.) 😊
One calorie is the quantity of energy (heat) needed to raise the temperature of 1g or ml of water by 1 degree. Given that a calorie is a relatively small unit, the term kilocalorie or Calorie is used to measure energy. A kcal/Calorie is equal to 1,000 calories and refers to the heat required to raise 1kg of water by 1 degree. The energy contained in the foods we consume is found in the chemical bonds of the macronutrient molecules. When these bonds are broken, energy is released and converted into another form of energy.
In absolute terms and in scientific theory, a calorie is a calorie, period. The first law of thermodynamics states that energy can neither be created nor destroyed, it can only be transformed from one form to another. Therefore, the human body is constantly transforming energy (i.e., chemical energy {calories} being transformed into another chemical energy {ATP} and then being transformed into mechanical energy and heat). But calories do not consider the effects of other variables on energy intake. Food quality is important and here are four variables that must be considered.
* Appetite
* Cravings
* Satiety
* Metabolic
There is much to consider especially given that the research shows that people really underestimate the calories they eat.

Supplementation is not absolutely necessary but it can be useful as long as you are reading labels and vetting the product. 
Here are my top 5 suggested supplements, covering the basics for physique optimization.
1.	Whey protein: It makes sense as a supplement for anyone. The protein in whey is very effective at triggering muscle protein synthesis due to its relatively high concentration of leucine. Whey protein contains between 10 and 13% leucine. By comparison, most meat, poultry, and fish top out, and about 8 to 9% leucine.
2.	Creatine: The benefits of creatine come from saturating your muscle cells with phosphocreatine. If you load, you can saturate your muscle cells faster, so if you load 15 to 20 grams per day, you’ll saturate your muscle cells within a week. But you’ll also saturate them if you just take a dose of three to five grams per day every day for about a month. It just depends on how quickly you want to get the results.
3.	Caffeine: It improves performance in the gym, increases your energy throughout the day, can increase strength, and help manage fatigue. This can be great as a pre-workout supplement when we want to be at our most alert and energetic.
4.	Fish oil: is a reliable source of omega-3 fatty acids, EPA, and DHA in particular. There’s very strong evidence that these fatty acids play a role in managing inflammation in the body and possibly decreasing soreness from exercise. There’s also evidence to have a direct benefit to net protein synthesis. EPA/DHA can both decrease muscle protein breakdown, and when taken with a meal, can help increase the natural boost and protein synthesis from food. Fish oil also seems to have a host of other health benefits as well.
5.	Rhodiola Rosea is an adaptogen. These are natural substances that help the body reach homeostasis and in the case of Rhodiola Rosea, it has the ability to reduce both actual fatigue and perceived fatigue as well as enhance cognition and the perception of wellbeing.

This post was inspired after reviewing my client’s squat in her training videos. I compiled a list of a circuit in preparation for properly squatting. The squat is one of the most fundamental movements a human needs to be able to perform both in life and the gym. In life, we use the squat to sit down and stand up from chairs or going down to the floor to reach for objects. In the strength training realm, the squat is a foundational exercise, but it is a complex movement requiring considerable strength and mobility out of the leg, hip, knee and ankle joints. From a mobility aspect, the squat requires flexion and extension of the hip, knee and ankle as well as some rotation from the hip. From a strength perspective, the squat requires the use of the quadriceps, hamstrings and glutes as well as the rotators of the hip in order to help control any medial or lateral movement of the knee. Being that the squat is such a complex movement, it is best to warm up properly for the squat when improving strength and mobility for everyday life movements or in preparation for a strength training session. Based on a recent client check-in, I decided to share my thoughts about making the decision to drink alcohol while in a fat-loss phase. This response is for a person with a goal to get very lean. That being the goal, I had a fairly specific response. And only through the client’s own self-discovery can then they determine if a drink is worth it. Being "shredded" requires extreme discipline so a firm decision has to be made.

Although alcohol is the subject, what I find the most interesting is the discovery through the situation.

A caveat here if we are looking at energy balance, this would apply to any food or drink that would take you outside of your caloric range and often happens in social situations.

Getting Honest:

1. Is drinking alcohol more of a habit than I originally believed it to be?

2. Do I have enough cognitive restraint to say no?

3. Is my desire to reach my goal strong enough?

If you said yes to the above the next steps are:

4. Do I have a reply ready and committed to when confronted with a situation that can take me away from my physique goal?

5. How can I set myself up for success in the midst of outside influence? The projections and belief systems of others become very evident.

6. Do you have a game plan for how to navigate that interaction?

There is much to consider beyond basic self-awareness, you must plan otherwise you risk getting sideswiped.

My advice is to get very clear and honest with yourself and then have a solid game plan in place.

I think this is why many people opt to stay home and until you have the above things determined it may be best.

Even though they went over their macros goals, because they did have the drink, this situation is an opportunity to go deeper in the resolve to stick to the plan.

Protein contains 4 kcal/gram.

Fats contain 9 kcal/gram.
Alcohol has 7 kcal/gram.

7 Signs Your Fat loss is Working.
"Working" is different for everyone but you could base the success of your diet on your personal health and performance goals. That being said, there is a range of agreed-upon progress markers indicating fat loss success.

WEIGHT: This is key and one of the most important. Fat loss will almost always come with weight loss, and you can monitor this quite easily using a body weight scale.

BODYFAT %: If you have access to measures of body fat and lean mass this will provide a more accurate measure of your fat loss progress. DEXA Scans are superior or a 9-sight skinfold bodyfat test works as well! 

CLOTHES FIT BETTER: This is especially for anyone who is strength training throughout a fat loss program. While the scales may not change much, if you are reducing fat mass, clothing will fit noticeably better.

POST-EXERCISE JOINT PAIN RELIEF: Carrying excess adiposity can lead to joint and muscle pain after exercise. One of the first things you'll begin to notice when losing weight is a reduction in this post-training joint pain.

MOOD: Excess fat mass can have a negative impact on mental health and well-being. If you are improving your body composition, health, and diet, you'll begin to notice the cognitive benefits too.

HEALTH MARKERS: Moving toward a healthy weight can have beneficial impacts on a range of health markers. If you currently have elevated levels of cholesterol, blood pressure, blood sugar, and more, these areas will most likely improve as body fat decreases.

CONFIDENCE: Even small changes in your weight, health, and/or fitness will have beneficial impacts on your confidence.

Having Trouble Hitting Your Macros while in a fat-loss phase?

The magic happens through preparation.

Step out in front of potential issues by making a non-negotiable game plan.

1. Determine daily caloric intake.

2. Based on that total, determine the macros goals for the day/each meal with a focus on adequate protein and fiber. 

3. Buy the Food

4. Input the exact food you bought into a food tracking App until you meet macros requirements. (Don't rely on foods already put in as they can be inaccurate or vastly different from the totals on the food you have)

5. Prepare the food

6. Measure and weigh the cooked food and put it into containers.

7. Put away measurement food in the refrigerator or freezer.

8. Bring prepared food with you when you leave the house. 🔑

If you consistently use this formula over the subsequent days, weeks, and months, you will be amazed at your success and increased compliance to macros goals.

Although this seems rather obvious and simple, some aspects are not so apparent. As professionals, it's easy to assume that people just know these steps. The post is based on obstacles from a few of my client check ins this week.

Taking the guesswork out of staying on track with food preparation. Let’s face it, how many times have you completely messed up your nutrition goals because you had to travel? If you are just starting out with a whole new lifestyle, are finally ready to get serious about your goals, or are a competitive physique athlete, then these suggestions are for you.
This may not be a popular post or opinion but meal preparation and making sure you have meals with you are non-negotiables. Truth be told, if you don't have every base covered in terms of meal planning, it is very easy to miss the mark regarding staying in a caloric deficit and on track. To go to the next level with your physique goals you may consider bringing meals with you to most places you go. There are other ways to be successful, such as locating food while you are out, but that takes a degree of planning as well, and it can create unnecessary stress. This applies to jumping in your car to go across town or boarding a plane, bringing meals with you is a game-changer! Sleep has a huge bearing on the immune system and poor quality sleep can also reduce the body's production of antibodies, which in turn makes you more susceptible to infection. Acute and chronic illnesses aside, the quantity and quality of sleep influence how efficiently you'll bounce back from the demands that daily life presents, which include but aren't limited to hectic work schedules, physical activity, and stress. 
Keeping my clients healthy is my top priority, so I track their sleep habits and create awareness around this aspect of their lives. It is impossible to recover from life stressors, and you can perpetually feel worn out and ill-equipped to handle everyday challenges, whether they be physical, mental, or emotional.
To boost immune health through sleep, remember that it's best to prioritize enough consistent, high-quality sleep to support strong immunity. 
Here is how:
• Keep a consistent bedtime schedule, ideally from 10:00 PM – 6:00 AM.
•	Block out light. In the run-up to bedtime, use lamps instead of overhead lighting. Then when it's time to go to sleep, block any light coming into your bedroom from outside. If there's lots of ambient light in your area, you might want to invest in blackout curtains to help with this. 
•	Reduce device use. You can track your device activity and even set timers to assist with limiting the length of time on your device at night.
Avoid any and all screens one hour before bed and turn off (or silence) nearby electronics. 
Lay off late-night alcohol use. This means no alcohol up to three hours before bedtime. (You know my stance on this subject)
•	Avoid stimulating activities close to bedtime. That means skipping late-night exercise, charged conversations, paying bills, watching the news, and similar activities should also be limited to help you drift off to sleep.
The first step is awareness, the next is the game plan. The last step is making a commitment to your immune system and overall recovery.

What Are Fats?

Fats are another essential micronutrient that is a rich source of energy but also serves many crucial roles such as: 
•	Hormone production 
•	Vitamin absorption
•	Protection of cells 
•	Insulation 

How much fat do I need?

Fat intake is relatively stable across different individuals. Of course, on more active days, it might be a good idea to bring fat intake slightly lower as it can cause stomach upset at times.
0.8 - 1.2 g/kg or 1 - 2 thumbs of fat per meal.

Saturated vs Unsaturated

These are the two overarching classifications of fat in our diet. These terms can seem confusing; however, it is actually quite easy to understand the difference. In saturated, the fatty acid is 'saturated' with hydrogen, resulting in a rigid structure (see below). Unsaturated fatty acids are not fully 'saturated' and will typically be liquid at room temperature.

Avoid saturated fat totally?

Saturated fat is not necessarily the enemy it has been made out to be. Excessive amounts are not healthy though and the American Heart Association recommends that saturates should make up 6% or less of energy intake.

Eating foods with fat is definitely part of a healthy diet. To choose healthier fats, use liquid non-tropical plant oils; low-fat or nonfat instead of full-fat dairy; and, if you eat meat, lean meat or poultry. And remember to balance the number of calories you eat from all foods with the number of calories you use through physical activity.

If you have contemplated the switch to a plant-based diet, it’s important to dig down into your motivations for doing so. If it is based on ethical reasons that is admirable and can be healthy, but supplementing will be necessary for optimal health. 

Here are nutrients that must be accounted for particularly if you are plant-based.

➡️ Protein

Combining protein sources (e.g., legumes and grains) and a plant-based protein supplement is really important.

➡️ Omega-3

Omega-3 fatty acids are consumed mostly in the form of ALA in vegetarian and vegan diets. This is inefficiently converted to EPA and DHA in the body, which we require in sufficient dosages. This can lead to suboptimal omega-3 status in vegetarians/vegans (Source: NCBI). One solution is Algae Oil.

➡️ Iron

Vegans with a low iron intake should aim to eat more iron-rich foods, such as cruciferous vegetables, beans, peas, dried fruit, nuts, and seeds. Iron-fortified foods, such as cereals, enriched bread, and plant milk, can further help. Vegetarians and vegans are recommended to consume 1.8x the amount of iron than omnivorous eaters. (Source: NIH)

➡️ Vitamin B12

Vitamin B12 can be consumed through a few select fortified vegan food products. Aside from these, it cannot be attained from plant foods and vegetarians and vegans have been shown to be at a higher risk of deficiency (Source: NCBI). B12-fortified foods commonly include plant milk, soy products, breakfast cereals, and nutritional yeast.

➡️ Calcium

Calcium is present in several plant foods, namely dark leafy greens. However, this is in far smaller dosages than in dairy foods and so vegetarians and vegans should include some fortified food/drink products in their habitual diet.

➡️ Vitamin D

The best way vegans can ensure they’re getting enough vitamin D is to have their blood levels assessed. Those unable to get enough from fortified foods and sunshine should consider taking a daily vitamin D2 or vegan vitamin D3 supplement.

➡️ Zinc

To maximize your intake, eat a variety of zinc-rich foods throughout the day. These include whole grains, wheat germ, tofu, sprouted breads, legumes, nuts and seeds.

Strength vs Hypertrophy

💪🏋️‍♀️ Strength training and hypertrophy training are both great approaches to weight training, but they have different goals, sets, reps, rest times, types, and lifts.

🏋️‍♂️ When it comes to strength training, your goal is to increase your maximal strength. Strength training, according to the National Strength and Conditioning Association (NSCA), involves using a high resistance load lifted for a smaller number of repetitions, typically 1-6 reps per set, for multiple sets. This type of training targets the fast-twitch muscle fibers, which are responsible for producing powerful contractions and are most responsible for strength.
In terms of rest, the NSCA recommends resting 2-5 minutes between sets to allow for sufficient recovery time and maximum effort during each set. 
References:
•	National Strength and Conditioning Association. (2018). Essentials of Strength Training and Conditioning. Human Kinetics.
•	American College of Sports Medicine. (2018). ACSM's Guidelines for Exercise Testing and Prescription. Wolters Kluwer.

🏋️‍♀️ Hypertrophy training, on the other hand, aims to increase muscle size. While there are a number of ways to induce hypertrophy in the weight room, it seems that employing multiple sets with moderate loads (6-12 reps, 65-85% 1RM) and rest periods (60 seconds) creates the greatest elevation of testosterone and growth hormone (primary anabolic hormones); compared to heavy loads (1-5 reps, >85% 1RM) with long rest periods (2-5 minutes) and light loads (12+ reps, <65% 1RM) with short rest periods (30 seconds) (Schoenfeld B. J., 2010). 

🏋️‍♂️ In terms of exercises, both types of training can include compound lifts like squats and deadlifts, as well as isolation exercises like bicep curls and leg extensions.

Progressive overload is the key to continued muscle growth and strength gains. Have you ever seen a person in the gym year after year looking exactly the same? There are several reasons this can occur, but if you are not challenging yourself in the gym and tracking your data, (sets/reps/loads) then you are not making valuable use of your training time. It is added work, but collecting this information is so important to progress.

There are several ways to progressively increase the intensity of your workouts over time. 

1. Add working sets. Increase the number of sets for each exercise. Adding just one set can significantly boost the volume and stimulate more muscle protein synthesis. 

2. Add repetition. Gradually increase the number of reps in each set. For example, if you can currently do 12 reps, aim for 13-15 reps in your next workout. 

3. Adjust tempo. Use a slower negative or faster positive phase to make each rep more difficult. This increases time under tension and muscle activation.
 
4. Add exercises. Include additional supportive exercises that work the same muscle groups. This exposure allows for greater recovery and adaptation. 

5. Reduce rest times. Take less rest between sets to keep your heart rate up and maintain higher intensity. Shorter rest periods enhance activation of the sympathetic nervous system for greater fat-burning and muscle gain.

Progressive overload is an ongoing process. Continue making small improvements to your routines and you will eventually really notice the difference!

Is fasted exercise superior for fat loss?

 🤔 There is a recent study that examined the effects of fasted exercise on energy balance, calorie consumption, hunger hormones, and energy expenditure. The study grouped participants into four categories and found that the fasted exercise group that did not have a standardized meal after the exercise had the highest subjective hunger rankings and a reduction in energy expenditure equivalent to about 10 calories per hour. 😋🍔 Doesn't seem like a lot but that can add up over the course of a day, reducing energy expenditure by about 240 kcal a day. 

For fat loss, the study revealed there was no difference in fat loss between fasted exercise and fed exercise groups when calories were controlled and equated over the course of weeks or months. 📈🏋️‍♀️

(PMID: 25429252 and 34674685)

The study did not assess exercise performance, and it is possible that fasting could lead to poor exercise performance. 💪

So here's the takeaway. People should do what they prefer and do what works best for them. I suggest making sure to eat a regular standardized meal within a few hours post exercise however to optimize energy expenditure throughout the day and to decrease hunger. 🍎 

The people that didn't eat after fasted training were quite obviously the hungriest! 😋

I personally prefer to eat before exercising, but I allow my clients to choose the number of meals they choose as well as meal timing. Adherence, whether fasted or not fasted, is what optimizes fat loss. Conversely, a benefit of training fasted is the decreased feeding window of the rest of the day. 💡 Did you know that fiber is essential for a healthy diet? Fiber regulates digestion, reduces the risk of heart disease and diabetes, and aids in weight management!
 
Consuming fiber on a regular basis helps you feel fuller for longer periods, prevents overeating, and makes sticking to a calorie-restricted diet more manageable. 

As a coach, I always recommend my clients consume the daily recommended amount of fiber, which can be easily calculated by dividing their total caloric intake by 1,000 and then multiplying it by 14. 

I find it helpful to target a range such as 25-30 grams per day to allow a bit of flexibility with the target goal for the day.

According to the research, only around 5% of Americans consume enough fiber, which is concerning because it's such an important nutrient for optimal health. 

That being said, a few adjustments to include more fibrous foods can make all the difference! So, let's make sure to include fiber-rich foods in our daily diet! 

One study published in the Annals of Internal Medicine found that participants who increased their fiber intake to 30 grams per day lost an average of 5 pounds (2.3 kg) in weight without making any other dietary changes. Another study showed that people who consumed 14 grams of fiber for every 1,000 calories lost an average of 4.5 pounds (2 kg) over a 4-month period. According to the National Institutes of Health and the Mayo Clinic, fiber is an essential nutrient and offers numerous health benefits. 

Check it out: https://medlineplus.gov/dietaryfiber.html and https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/nutrition-and-healthy-eating/in-depth/fiber/art-20043983.

🌟Study Alert: Plant-Based Protein Packs a Punch for Muscle Growth🌟

A recent randomized controlled study discovered that plant-based nutrition can be equally effective as milk-based protein for muscle protein synthesis. This is fantastic news for those wanting to include more plant-based protein in their diet without sacrificing muscle growth and recovery.💪🌱

🔍Study Breakdown:
The study, titled "The Muscle Protein Synthetic Response to the Ingestion of a Plant-Derived Protein Blend Does Not Differ from an Equivalent Amount of Milk Protein in Healthy Young Males," aimed to compare muscle protein synthesis between plant-derived protein blends and milk protein in healthy young men.

👨‍🔬Twelve healthy young men participated in the study, receiving either a plant-based protein blend or milk protein. Researchers measured muscle protein synthesis rates using stable isotope methodology and found no significant differences between the two groups.

🌿💪The study challenges the widely held belief that plant-based protein sources are less effective for promoting muscle protein synthesis than animal-based sources. The results indicate that consuming a blend of plant-based proteins can provide similar anabolic benefits as milk protein.

Ready for a refreshing Summer Salad that will get you closer to your protein requirements? Here is a Summer Salad! 

Chickpea, Quinoa, and Spinach Salad:

Ingredients:
- 1 cup cooked quinoa (cooked according to package directions)
- 1 15-ounce can of chickpeas, drained and rinsed
- 3 cups baby spinach, chopped
- 1/2 cup cherry tomatoes, halved
- 1/2 English cucumber, diced
- 1/4 cup red onion, finely diced
- 2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
- 2 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
- 2 tablespoons chopped fresh mint
- 3 tablespoons lemon juice
- 1 tablespoon olive oil
- 1 clove garlic, minced
- Salt and pepper, to taste

Instructions:
1. In a large mixing bowl, combine the cooked quinoa, chickpeas, spinach, cherry tomatoes, cucumber, red onion, parsley, cilantro, and mint.
2. In a small bowl, whisk together the lemon juice, olive oil, garlic, salt, and pepper.
3. Pour the dressing over the salad and mix well to combine.
4. Taste and adjust seasoning as needed.
5. Serve chilled or at room temperature.

Macros breakdown (per serving, assuming 4 servings):
- Protein: 30g
- Carbs: 20g
- Fat: 11g

Feel free to adjust the recipe to reach your desired macros. For example, you can increase the amount of chickpeas or quinoa to reach a higher protein goal or reduce the amount of olive oil to reduce fat content. To serve the salad with a beautiful presentation, use a large platter and garnish with extra herbs or some lemon wedges.

Active recovery is indeed beneficial for post-workout recovery as it can enhance blood flow and nutrient delivery to muscles, facilitating the removal of metabolite build-up like lactic acid and reducing soreness. There are numerous ways to engage in active recovery, and the most important factor is finding what works best for you. Aim to dedicate around 30-60 minutes to your chosen activity.

In this post, I've outlined four common methods of active recovery on rest days:

1️⃣ Walking: Walking is a convenient and accessible option that can be enjoyed anywhere. It can also be a wonderful opportunity to spend time with friends while promoting recovery.

2️⃣ Yoga: Many athletes find great benefits in practicing yoga. With a combination of poses, breathing techniques, and mindful meditation, yoga can help you unwind, enhance flexibility, and build strength. You can easily find beginner yoga routines online or join a local class.

4️⃣ Cycling: Cycling, whether indoors or outdoors, can be an excellent choice for active recovery. When done at a leisurely pace, it promotes blood flow, gets your heart pumping, and allows your muscles to recover while enjoying a ride.

Active recovery should not be done at an intensity that pushes you beyond your limits. It's crucial to listen to your body and choose activities that provide rejuvenation and recharge.

There are several ways to manipulate training variables to achieve progressive overload:

1. Sets: Increasing the number of sets you perform for a particular exercise can help increase the overall volume and intensity of your training. For example, if you typically perform 3 sets of squats, you can gradually increase it to 4 sets over several weeks.

2. Load: Manipulating the amount of weight you lift is a common method of progressive overload. You can increase the load by adding additional weight in small increments. For example, if you are currently squatting 120 lbs, you can gradually increase it to 125 lbs, and then further increase it to 130 lbs over time.

3. Duration: Manipulating the duration or length of your workouts can also contribute to progressive overload. You can gradually increase the total time spent on a particular exercise or increase the duration of your entire training session.

4. Frequency: Manipulating the frequency at which you train can also help achieve progressive overload. This can be done by increasing the number of training sessions per week or by adding additional exercises to your existing routine. For example, if you currently train legs twice a week, you can consider adding a third leg day to increase the overall workload.

It's important to note that progressive overload should be implemented in a gradual and progressive manner. It's not advisable to jump from 120 lbs. to 135 lbs. overnight. The body needs time to adapt and handle the increased stress. Gradually increase the difficulty of your workouts over time to ensure safety and effectiveness.

Remember, the specific form of progressive overload you choose is up to you and your individual goals. The key is to have a systematic approach to progressively making your training more challenging and pushing yourself to new limits. This continuous adaptation and progression will help drive continuous improvements in strength and overall progress.

This is only one way, you can decrease rest times, increase time under tension, change the tempo and use advanced training techniques. There is so much to say here, but understanding the foundation is so important.

Today, I want to share some of the incredible variety of plant-based protein sources that are available.

RPE (Rate of Perceived Exertion) helps gauge your workout intensity on a scale of 1-10. Similar to Reps In Reserve, it's used to adjust your weights for optimal challenge. 

Consider these examples:

Example 1: You're doing 3 sets x 8 reps at RPE 7, three reps from failure. Using 20-pound dumbbells feels easy, and you rate it as RPE 5. It's time to increase the weight in the next set.

Example 2: Same scenario, but the 20-pound dumbbells feel heavy, making your RPE 9. It's time to decrease the weight in the next set.

RPE can also track progress. If you lift the same weight and reps, but your RPE decreases, you've made progress. 

RPE improves your workout understanding and optimizes your performance. It requires honest self-assessment to adapt to your capacity effectively. Trust me, it's a game-changer!

💪 Myth #1: High-Protein Diets Are Bad for the Kidneys in General.

💪 Myth #2: Animal Protein is a Must for Maximizing Muscle Growth.

🕒⏰ DOES MEAL TIMING INFLUENCE FAT LOSS? ⏰🕒

🍽️ We all know that energy balance is crucial for weight loss - maintaining a calorie deficit is key. But did you know that the time of day you eat could also play a role in this equation? A fascinating study published in Cell explored the effects of eating at different times of the day on hunger and appetite-regulating hormones. The results were eye-opening! 👀

🔄 Participants were split into two groups: Group 1 ate at 8 am, 12 pm, and 4 pm, while Group 2 had their meals at 12 pm, 4 pm, and 8 pm. Importantly, both groups consumed the same amount of food and calories, with physical activity and sleep carefully controlled.

📅 On Test Day 1 (Study Day 3), the differences became evident. Late-night eating was associated with higher levels of hunger throughout the day compared to early morning eating. This could be attributed to the Ghrelin to leptin ratio being greater throughout the day during late-night eating. Ghrelin, the hunger hormone, increases appetite, while leptin, the satiety hormone, helps to curb it.

💪 But here's the exciting part: early morning eating led to significantly higher total daily energy expenditure. In other words, eating more food earlier in the day appeared to boost energy expenditure and positively impact hunger and satiety.

📚 So, what's the takeaway from this study? Energy balance remains crucial for weight loss, and being in a calorie deficit is essential. Meal timing, and incorporating more food into your day during the morning hours may be one more strategy to implement to regulate your body weight. 🏋️‍♂️

This is just one study, what is important is that you find and implement a strategy that you can sustain. It may not only be about what you eat but also when you eat it. 

Try various times of the day to eat to determine if eating earlier in the day is a fat loss strategy for you! 🌟

Wondering how to tweak your training volume for maximum muscle growth? Here are a few of my thoughts on the subject.

Training volume for muscle growth is essentially the number of sets you perform to near-failure. Increasing this volume can increase muscle growth, but only up to a point. 

Think of this as where the 'magic happens' regarding muscle growth. Going above this optimal range could lead to stagnation and ultimately regression in your progress. 

The tricky part? This optimal place varies for each individual and it's difficult to determine exactly when and by how much to increase sets for optimal muscle growth. That being said, you need to be open to try!

Here's a guide to help you figure this out:

1. Start with a baseline volume that allows growth. Research suggests an optimal range of 10-20 sets per muscle group per week. Yet, you're free to begin at a lower point if that suits you better. 

2. Gradually increase your reps or load over time. For instance, you might go from 3 sets of 10 reps at 30 lbs, to 3 sets of 11 reps at the same weight, or keep the reps the same and up your weight to 35 lbs.

3. If you hit a performance plateau, consider adding some extra sets each week for that specific muscle group. 

Which leads me to ...

4. You can also introduce more 'warm-up sets', progressively intensifying them, as another way to add volume without pushing too close to failure. Program in the warm up sets, then increase their RPE, voila a working set! 

5. Before cranking up your volume, ensure your recovery game is strong. Prioritize nutrition, stress management, and make sure you get adequate sleep.

Remember, continuous weekly progress isn't a must. A true plateau means no advancement over several weeks in spite of optimal recovery. 

Be flexible with your volume goals as they may need to change over time and can vary between different muscle groups. 👀

But it doesn't end with exercise. In a separate experiment on hunger and satiety, individuals informed they possessed the "good" gene felt more satisfied after eating a standardized meal and even showed higher levels of satiety hormones. 🧑‍🔬🍽️

These studies highlight the immense power of our minds.

💪🧠 Your self-beliefs, shaped by the information you consume and your mindset, can profoundly impact your physical experiences and performance. Remember, you are in control of your mindset and the information you choose to consume. ✨💫

🏋️‍♂️💦 Don't let the fear of "holding water" make you forget that ~ 70% of your muscle tissue is WATER! 

👉 Hydration on the day of the show is KEY. Without it, achieving that perfect pump on stage becomes impossible. You might think you're "spilled over," but you're actually just flat. 

🍚💦 You Finally get some Carbs! Yes and remember, water plays a crucial role in storing glucose in the muscles as glycogen. When increasing your carb intake, ensure you're drinking enough water to transport the glycogen into the muscle. If not you can experience bloating and other unintended consequences! 

💦🔬 Intracellular fluid (inside the muscle) vs extracellular fluid (outside the muscle) - that's the game. Dehydration increases blood osmolality, which causes water to shift from inside to outside the muscle. This is why some competitors seem to be "holding water" on stage. 

So, what's the solution? 🤔

🎯 Your goal should be to be ready in advance where you don't need to do anything but show up! Ok, maybe not that simplified but experimenting with water and sodium levels can be risky. Better to maintain consistency without attempting a 'brotocol.'

💧To prevent 'spilling over', you MUST drink water on the day of the show. It might be less than usual, but you still need to hydrate to bring the nutrients into the cells. You will not 'spill over'. You just need to time your water intake right! 💪💦

🏋️‍♀️ Is going to failure essential for maximizing strength and muscle development? Research says not necessarily, especially if your goal is just to stay healthy and in shape. Here's the scoop:

🔥 Muscle Stimulation: Reaching failure ensures full stimulation of muscle type 2 fibers, crucial for developing a robust physique.

💪 Effective Training: Teaches you to use RPE/RIR for more effective workouts, giving you better control over your training outcomes.

🧠 Psychological Benefits: Pushing your limits can be enjoyable, offering psychological benefits beyond physical gains.

🚨 Exercise Caution: While occasional failure is okay, be cautious, especially with big movements like deadlifts and squats. Reserve it for the last set to avoid compromising quality.

💡 Tip: Use failure more frequently for targeted exercises like calf raises and bicep curls.

Remember, it's not always necessary, but understanding when and how to push yourself to the limit can enhance your training experience! 💪

Are you looking to unlock your full strength potential? This latest meta-analysis might have just the key you need! 📊🔑

A deep dive into 24 diverse studies has revealed a game-changing fact for both gym newbies and seasoned lifters alike. When it comes to strength training, SPEED is your friend! 💪⏱️

The evidence states that performing concentric movements (that's the 'lifting' part of your reps) in LESS than two seconds can lead to significantly greater strength increases than taking it slow. This holds true regardless of your training background!

Why does this work? It's all about motor unit recruitment. Explosive movements ensure that you're making the most out of each and every rep by maximizing the activation of your muscle fibers. 🧠💡

So, what's the takeaway for your training regimen? If strength is your main goal, aim to lift with MAXIMUM concentric velocity. This approach not only builds raw power but also enhances the maximal voluntary muscular activation, boosting the effectiveness of your future workouts. 🚀🏋️

In summary lift those weights and keep it moving! 😁
